. In tracing the development of human influence on plant life, Anderson focuses particularly on crops, which he reveals as having started out as weeds--hybrids that sprang up from the dump heaps and gardens of early humans. His investigation of the tangled and continuing history of weeds and cultivated plants ranges from autumnal European greens and the American sunflower to backyard landscapes in developing countries, where fruit trees, flowers, vines, and vegetables mingle with the sources for fibers, poisons, narcotics, and other drugs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBotany, Economic. 0aBotany. 0aPlants and civilization. 4aapplied ecology. 4abiology. 4abotany. 4adevelopment. 4aenvironmental science. 4aethnology. 4aevolution. 4aflow. 4agenetics. 4ageography. 4ahistory of biology. 4ahistory of life sciences. 4alandscapes. 4alife sciences. 4aplant sciences. 4aplants. 4asources. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Botany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052030792640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520312548?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520312548423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520312548/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles